Its Teacher Tuesday! Each Tuesday we will spotlight a few of our faculty and staff members! This weeks spotlight is our Upper Elementary Staff. Be sure to click on their photos for some fun facts about them!

Mrs. Tindle is the 5th grade teacher. She has been teaching at CISD for 24 years!

Mrs. Cox is the 4th grade teacher. This is her 10th year teaching at CISD.

Ms. Seibert is the 4th grade substitute for Mrs. Coxs maternity leave. She officially retired in January after teaching at CISD for 29 years! We are happy to have her back in the building.

Mrs. Embry is the 3rd grade teacher. She has been teaching at CISD for 13 years!

post_text: Ace Academy will begin on Tuesday, September 8, 2020. We will begin virtually until we are allowed to return to school and work face to face. We will be setting up a Google Meets account that we will be using as well as making phone calls to check-in with our students and families. We will be available to help your student with homework and provide some at home activities that you can play as a family. If you would like to register your child(ren) for Ace Academy or have any questions please contact us at (270)788-3910 EXT. 204

post_text: This is just a reminder that students will begin the school year on August 24th with at home learning. Students in kindergarten, 1st, and 2nd grades will complete paper-based work. Students in 3rd through 12th grades will complete their work online. This will continue through at least September 25th. More details will be released as soon as possible. If you do not have internet access at home, please call school at (270) 788-3388 and let us know so that we can make plans for you. Also, high school students may pick up their Chromebooks at school tomorrow, Thursday, or Friday between 8:00 and 2:00 each day.

post_text: In conjunction with the recommendation of Governor Andy Beshear, CISD will delay the start of in person classes until at least September 28th. We had already planned to begin with at least two weeks of at home learning on August 24th, so we will simply extend this. The schedule for Chromebook pickup this week and next will continue as planned. We will provide further details about at home learning as soon as possible.

post_text:
From the Cloverport School Food Service Team,



Due to the delay of students returning to in-person classes, we will be continuing our food pick-up program. If you have been participating in the food pick-up program this summer, we will have food boxes ready for you to pick up on next Monday, August 10th and each following Monday until we resume in-person classes. If you have not been participating, but would like to start, please complete this survey to register. We will need to receive your registration by the Wednesday before a Monday pick-up to ensure we have enough supplies to fulfill your request. If you have any questions, please contact Laura Shultz at laura.shultz@cloverport.kyschools.us or (270)788-3388 ext. 132.

post_text: The Kentucky Department of Education has recommended that, due to the continued increase in active cases of COVID-19 in the state, school districts with a start date on or before August 14, 2020 consider beginning with at home learning or moving their start date. Please complete the reopening survey on our district website (cloverport.kyschools.us) to assist us in planning. If you have questions, please reach out directly to Superintendent Keith Haynes at (270) 788-3388 x 113 or keith.haynes@cloverport.kyschools.us. (We do not read or reply to Facebook comments.)

We have created an FAQ page where we are posting questions we receive about reopening. If you have specific questions, please call Mr. Haynes at (270) 788-3388 x 113 or email him at keith.haynes@cloverport.kyschools.us. We only loosely monitor Facebook, so PLEASE use phone or email instead!

Also, if you require more time to decide if at home or in person learning is best for your child, you may wait until Friday, July 24th to let us know your intentions. We fully understand how important this decision is!

Things are constantly changing, so please know that no part of our reopening plan is set in stone! We will do what we believe is in the best interest of our staff and students.

Thanks...and hang in there :)

post_text:
Tomorrow is the first day of drop offs/pick ups!
Students will be able to come to school to turn in computers, books, guitars, and pick up any medication that may have been stored in the Nurse's Office as well as belongings left in lockers.

Social distancing must be observed at all times. Teachers will be here for you to say goodbye to them. Parent/Guardians please drive to the front of the school and teachers will be waiting. Please stay in your car in order to abide by social distancing. We do not want anybody to get out of the vehicle. Teachers will take anything you have to turn in and if your child has any belongings left at school, they will be in a bag for you to take with you. If you have more than one child that attends and want to do everything at one time, we will be able to accommodate you. I cannot promise that all teachers will be here at that time though. If these dates do not work for you, please contact the school at 270-788-3388.
See the picture below for all dates and times.

post_text: Students in Ms. Johnsons high school science class did an experiment on bacteria growth. They took slices of white bread and rubbed them on an object. They were then put into baggies to watch as bacteria from that surface grew. Makes you realize how important it is to wash your hands after coming into contact with everyday things!

Western Kentucky Regional Blood Center announced the Class Of 2020 High School Heroes! These seniors have donated blood 4 times and will receive an award and a solid red Honor Cord to wear at graduation! FFHS is proud to have Joseph Gedling and Emily King make the list!

**Attention High School Seniors**
If you have donated blood 3 times and need one more, there's still time! Email schedule@wkrbc.org to schedule your last donation for High School Hero Awards.
If you have donated 4 times please e-mail Vicki@wkrbc.org. Include your name and school so we can get your awards to you. I have a working list but inevitably will miss some of you.
WKRBC supports the Class of 2020! Help us get your awards to you

Since our teachers and staff miss our students so much, we will be having a parade through town to visit our students! The parade will begin at 12:15 at CISD and will travel through all roads in Cloverport up to HWY 60 and 144. Please come out and wave and shout hello from your porches or yards. We will NOT be stopping, so please stay in your yard. Remember to practice safe social distancing and do not gather in groups or yards other than your own.

You will be able to hear us coming! So please be patient and ready to wave when we drive by!

post_text:
The Cloverport Independent School District is pleased to announce the recent establishment of the CISD Athletic Hall of Fame. The mission of the Athletic Hall of Fame is to honor the extraordinary players of Cloverport Athletics, preserve its history, promote its value, and celebrate excellence everywhere. For more than a century and a half, CISD has produced competitive athletic competition, and we want to honor the Cloverport Community- its players, its legends, its history, and its core set of values.

If you would like to make a donation to aid in the development of the Athletic Hall of Fame, please mail checks made payable to Cloverport Independent Schools to the attention of CISD Athletic Hall of Fame, 301 Poplar Street, Cloverport, KY 40111. All donations will be used to create, update, and maintain the Athletic Hall of Fame project.

Additionally, nomination forms are also available at www.cloverport.kyschools.us. Nominations are accepted between April 1st and May 1st of each year.

锔ACES LITTLE LIBRARY 锔
***Take a Book/Give a Book***

Campbell Moore, a 4th grade student at WNES, decided this year for her GT project (in addition to her "Pop It and Drop It" soda tab campaign) she wanted to create a Free Little Library for her community.

She spent all winter planning, building, and painting it with the help of her dad, Nathan Moore. It is located at Bert's and is now open for business!

The Cloverport Schools STLP team created an awesome QR Code system that will help people locate the library and also future Little Libaries around our community. STLP also did a book drive and collected several books that will go in the library!

They will be adding more books over the next few days but if you have some books laying around the house, feel free to add it to the library! If you know of a child who loves books, please, take one from the library! *You dont have to give a book to take one!*

text:
锔ACES LITTLE LIBRARY 锔
***Take a Book/Give a Book***

Campbell Moore, a 4th grade student at WNES, decided this year for her GT project (in addition to her "Pop It and Drop It" soda tab campaign) she wanted to create a Free Little Library for her community.

She spent all winter planning, building, and painting it with the help of her dad, Nathan Moore. It is located at Bert's and is now open for business!

The Cloverport Schools STLP team created an awesome QR Code system that will help people locate the library and also future Little Libaries around our community. STLP also did a book drive and collected several books that will go in the library!

They will be adding more books over the next few days but if you have some books laying around the house, feel free to add it to the library! If you know of a child who loves books, please, take one from the library! *You dont have to give a book to take one!*

Way to go Campbell and the STLP team! We are proud of you! 锔

post_text: This week has been all about heart health and hygiene! Students learned all about what is good or bad for your heart, and then got to participate in a fun cardio relay race that included trying to get the most number of correct items either put under the heart (good for you) or in the trash can (bad for you). In the hygiene lessons, students participated in a jeopardy face off with trivia questions about daily personal hygiene, garment care, and dental health! Students were gifted a special Valentines Day Treat at the end of the lesson.
